The Road to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament present one of the most challenging tasks the world faces today. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global well-being and find solutions to problems that transcend borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a supreme public good of utmost importance.
My interest in this topic is partly rooted in personal experience.
My home country, South Korea, has suffered from the devastation of conventional warfare and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
However, such threat scenarios do exist not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons really sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Yet, the UN plays a crucial role in this process.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed goals and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to give up on nuclear weapons and summarized their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which primarily explains the estimated 26,000 still existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and raising new risks that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world is still concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns peacefully.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as atomic energy is seen as a clean energy alternative during times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this could lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that needs to be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
But the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us consider the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Studies), military expenditures rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating that the total costs of nuclear weapons alone in the United States amounted to over $5.8 trillion, including future decommissioning costs.
This is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Reflections on the costs of nuclear weapons and the inherent dangers associated with them have sparked a global idea fire, potentially breathing new life into the cause of nuclear disarmament.
We experienced the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven-Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan founded the International Commission on Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil society groups and nuclear-armed states have also put forward proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
Firstly: I call on all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and engage in negotiations for effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate an arms convention supported by a strong control system, as has been proposed for a long time in the UN.
I have shared a draft for such a convention, which provides a good starting point, with all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world.
The world would also welcome the resumption of bilateral negotiations between the US and Russia aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK's proposal for a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of controls is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues within the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it known to states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapon use or threat thereof.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoria on nuclear testing and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as incentives for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without preconditions take up discussions on a treaty regarding fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urge all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily adopt the stricter security clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they plan to do to achieve these goals.
Yet these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to urge the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their wider dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons underscores the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism involving weapons of mass destruction, limiting the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new weapon bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
As real, verified progress in disarmament is made, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the world's most deadly weapons and their components, we make it harder to carry out terrorist attacks using weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a fresh start not only for disarmament but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
